[2]
Date: Sun 26 Jun 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Monsters and Critics [edited]
<http://news.monstersandcritics.com/health/article_1022537.php/Two_die_of_plague_after_eating_marmot_in_Chinas_Tibet_region_>


2 die of plague after eating marmot in China's Tibet region
-----------------------------------------------------------
2 people died of plague, and 3 others were hospitalized, after they ate
marmot meat in a remote area of China's Tibet region, state media said on
Sun 26 Jun 2005.

The 5 migrant road workers became ill after eating marmot on 11 Jun 2005 in
Tibet's Zhongba county, close to China's border with Nepal, the official
Xinhua news agency said. Doctors treated the 5 workers for an unspecified
form of plague, but 2 of them died in the hospital, the agency said.

Health officials quarantined 75 people who had contact with the infected
workers, but none showed plague-like symptoms. Police were also trying to
trace a woman who had contact with the infected people but crossed the
border into Nepal on 21 Jun 2005.

The health ministry reported the infections to the WHO and the Nepalese
government on Sat 25 Jun 2005, the agency said. The most common form is the
bubonic plague, which became known as the "black death" after a major
outbreak spread to Europe from Central Asia in the 14th century. Some
experts believe the Black Death 1st spread to humans through contact with
marmots, which are still commonly hunted for food by Mongolians.

Smaller outbreaks of bubonic plague are frequently reported in remote areas
of north western China and Mongolia. In 2004, plague outbreaks linked to
marmot hunting killed 8 and infected at least 11 others in a remote area of
Qinghai province, which occupies the northern half of the Tibetan plateau.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dan Silver for contributing the 1st posting. We would
appreciate more information regarding the manifestations of plague in these
individuals. The form of _Yersinia pestis_ infection is not stated here,
but the institution of quarantine in contacts suggests that a plague
pneumonia may have been present as a primary or secondary manifestation. -
Mod.LL]
